{
  "doc_id": "50458",
  "text": "Nosocomial transmission of hepatitis B virus has been documented since at least the early 1980s, 48,49 although the phenomenon was described more frequently and in ever more surprising forms in the 1990s. [CITATION_1] Hepatitis B vaccines have not only resulted in global reductions in the burden of liver disease caused by hepatitis B virus, but also have conferred protection in the healthcare setting, especially for healthcare workers. [CITATION_2] The importance of widespread community-based hepatitis B vaccination is highlighted by the recognition that some patients in healthcare facilities, such as those receiving hemodialysis, respond poorly to the vaccine, and thus depend on herd protection. [CITATION_3] ",
